  / HTML: Important Tags
  %section#important-tags
    %h1 Important Tags

    %p
      Some elements only appear once per HTML document:
      %br
      = succeed ", " do
        %a( href="http://www.w3schools.com/tags/tag_doctype.asp" target="_blank" )DOCTYPE
      = succeed ", " do
        %a( href="http://www.w3schools.com/tags/tag_html.asp" target="_blank" ) html
      = succeed ", " do
        %a( href="http://www.w3schools.com/tags/tag_head.asp" target="_blank" ) head
      = succeed ", " do
        %a( href="http://www.w3schools.com/tags/tag_title.asp" target="_blank" ) title
      and
      = succeed "." do
        %a( href="http://www.w3schools.com/tags/tag_body.asp" target="_blank" ) body

    %pre
      %code( data-trim="" )
        :preserve
          &lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
          &lt;html&gt;
            &lt;head&gt;
              &lt;title&gt;&lt;/title&gt;
            &lt;/head&gt;
            &lt;body&gt;
            &lt;/body&gt;
          &lt;/html&gt;

    %ul.text--smaller.text--left
      %li
        Technically the
        %code &lt;!DOCTYPE&gt;
        declaration is not an HTML tag; it is an instruction to the web browser about what version of HTML the page is written in.
      %li
        The
        %code &lt;html&gt;
        tag tells the browser that this is an HTML document.
      %li
        The
        %code &lt;body&gt;
        tag defines the document's body.

  / HTML: Self-Closing Tags
  %section#self-closing-tags
    %h1 Self-Closing Tags

    %p
      Some start tags are self-closing, or void elements, and do not require end tags.
      A void element's behaviour is predefined, and it can not contain any content or other elements.

    %p
      To specify that it is a void element, a "/" is included at the end of the tag. In HTML5, the "/" is not required - it's just syntax sugar for some coders. Yet, the distinction is important since (in the HTML syntax at least)
      %strong &lt;div /&gt;
      means
      %strong &lt;div&gt;
      in HTML5 and not
      %strong &lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
      as it does in
      = succeed "." do
        %a( href="http://www.w3schools.com/html/html_xhtml.asp" target="_blank" ) XHTML

    %p
      %strong We will be using HTML5 syntax. Some examples:

    %pre
      %code( data-trim="" )
        :preserve
          &lt;meta name="author" content="Stefanie"&gt;
          &lt;img src="http://placekitten.com/500/500"&gt;
          &lt;br&gt;
          &lt;hr&gt;

